When compiling #link("https://www.nist.gov/services-resources/software/nist-biometric-image-software-nbis", "NBIS"), normally, the source's Makefile automatically determines whether to use little endian based on the system environment. However, in practice, this configuration does not work on my system.

= Environment

System: Ubuntu 22.04 WSL2

= Problem

The NBIS toolkit is used to parse WSQ files. WSQ data files are arranged in big-endian byte order. Initially, I was unaware of the endian issue and directly compiled the library and then called the parser. Normally, big-endian data would automatically convert to little-endian during memory copying. However, after reading the data from the WSQ file and performing a direct memory copy, I found that the data was not correctly converted, resulting in reversed byte markers:

```
// Big-endian marker in the data (the correct marker the program should read)
0xFF 0xA0
// Little-endian marker in memory after conversion (the incorrect marker the program reads)
0xA0 0xFF
```

After examining the source code, I found that in the data reading function `getc_ushort`, the program checks a `__NBISLE__` macro to determine whether to swap the two bytes:

```c
#ifdef __NBISLE__
   swap_short_bytes(shrt_dat);
#endif
```

However, this macro is generated by the Makefile but does not take effect. I tried various methods of passing parameters through the make command, but none worked.

= Solution

Ultimately, I decided to modify the source code directly, hardcoding the `__NBISLE__` macro:

```c
#ifndef __NBISLE__
#define __NBISLE__ 1
#endif
```

This ensures that the program will definitely read the `__NBISLE__` macro when reading.

After some AI assistance and searching, I determined the necessary changes to be:

- Add the macro definition in `commonnbis/include/defs.h`
- Include the above header file in `imgtools/include/ioutil.h`

After making these modifications and recompiling, the program finally correctly reads the big-endian marker from the data.
